    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="bibliography">
                <p>Copied by Pistelli, and published from a letter <bibl><ptr target="pareti1912"/> <citedRange>304-305</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                   <bibl><ptr target="Sammelbuch"/> <citedRange>3.6017</citedRange>, <citedRange>3.6018</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="phi"/> <citedRange><ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/222092">222092</ref></citedRange>, 
                        <citedRange><ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/222093">222093</ref></citedRange></bibl>,
                    <bibl><ptr target="christoph1966"/> <citedRange>22, 23</citedRange></bibl>,  
                    <bibl> <ptr target="cameronCF"/> <citedRange unit="page">148</citedRange>, <citedRange unit="page">317</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    copied by Walker and published  <bibl><ptr target="flinders1925"/> <citedRange unit="page">13</citedRange></bibl>.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
               <div type="textpart" n="i"><ab>
                <lb n="1"/>   <g ref="symbol.xml#crux"/> <persName type="emperor" ref="#phocas"><name nymRef="Φωκᾶς">Φωκᾶ</name> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <addName nymRef="εὐσεβέστατος"><w lemma="εὐσεβής">εὐ
              <lb n="2" break="no"/>ϲεβεϲτάτου</w></addName>
                <lb n="3"/><w lemma="ἡμεῖς">ἡμῶν</w> <w lemma="δεσπότης">δεσπό
                <lb n="4" break="no"/>του</w></persName> <w lemma="πολύς">πολλὰ</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τὰ</w>  
                    <lb n="5"/><space/> <w lemma="ἔτος">ἔτη</w> <space/></ab></div>
            <div type="textpart"  n="ii"><ab>
                <lb n="1"/><w lemma="τόπος">Τόποϲ</w> <w lemma="διαφέρω">διαφέρ
               <lb n="2" break="no"/> <space/> ων </w>
            <lb n="3"/><orgName ref="#blue" nymRef="#οἱ Βένετοι"><w lemma="ὁ">τοῖϲ</w>  <w lemma="βένετος">Βενέτοιϲ</w></orgName></ab> </div>
                
    
     
     </div>
            <div type="apparatus"><listApp>
                
                <app loc="i.1"><rdg resp="#flinders1925">. . . ΦΩΚΑΙΟΥ</rdg></app>
                <app loc="i.1/2"><note>Pistelli reported, in a later letter, that he could read ΕΥ, but he did not make clear whether this was at the end of line 1 or the beginning of 
                line 2.</note></app>
                <app loc="i.2"><rdg resp="#flinders1925">(ΕΥ)ϹΕΒΕϹΤΑΤΟΥ</rdg></app>
                <app loc="i.3"><rdg resp="#flinders1925">(0ΙΚ)ΕΙΩΝ ΔΕϹΠΟ</rdg></app>
                <app loc="ii.1"><rdg resp="#flinders1925">ΑΝΑΦΕΡΟ(ΝΤΩΝ)</rdg></app>
                <app loc="ii.2"><rdg resp="#flinders1925"> . . . ΝΕ . . . .</rdg></app></listApp></div>
             
            <div type="translation" source="#flinders1925" xml:lang="en">
                
                <p><note>i</note>: Of Phocaeus, a most pious master of his household for many years</p>
            </div>  
           <div type="translation" resp="#cmr" xml:lang="en">
              
               <p><note>i</note>: Many years for Phocas, our most pious lord!</p> 
               <p><note>ii</note>: Place belonging to the Blues</p>
                
         </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>For the history of the column see <ref target="http://www.papyrology.ox.ac.uk/POxy/VExhibition/the_site/phocas-pillar.html">Oxyrhynchus: A City and its Texts, Virtual Exhibition: The Site</ref>. 
                    By 1981 some traces of text i could still be seen, but almost nothing of text ii. In spring 2019 the <ref target="https://www.oxirrinc.com/en/el-yacimiento/columna-honorifica/">excavation team from the University of Barcelona</ref>, led by Professor Josep Padró i Parcerisa, examined the column closely, 
                    and could find no trace of either text; I am most grateful to Professor Padró for his help.</p>
                <p>For this kind of composite structure compare the σύνθετος κίων. erected in 609 in Constantinople for Phocas, 
                    <ref target="http://laststatues.classics.ox.ac.uk/database/detail.php?record=LSA-2775">LSA 2275</ref>. We cannot determine with certainty the 
                    relationship of the two texts to one another, although Pistelli observed that the scripts were similar: Del  tutto  simile  è  la  scrittura  delle  due  iscrizioni.. </p>
                
            </div>
            
